  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Action for Cultural and Religious Pluralism in Niger and Nigeria</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Niger and Nigeria are bordering countries situated in West Africa. Niger is one of the lowest-ranked in the UN HDI whereas Nigeria has a large economy and is listed among the &quot;Next Eleven&quot;, a list of economies that are set to become among the biggest in the world (Goldman Sachs, 2012). Niger is a francophone country and Nigeria an anglophone; even though Nigeria is inhabited by over 500 ethnic groups, speaking 500 different languages (World Atlas, 2017). Islam accounts for 94% of Niger&#x2019;s religious adherents. Nigeria is nearly equally divided between Christianity and Islam. Two different countries but when looking at the political, economic, social, technological, legal and environmental root causes and effects of decreased tolerance for cultural and religious pluralism, Niger and Nigeria show a lot of similarities.
As demonstrated, Nigeria and Niger are multi-ethnic, multi-lingual and multi-religious countries. The culture of both countries is shaped by its diverse groups; hence, religion is conflated with ethnicity and regionalism. In the Call for Proposals, intercultural dialogue may include interreligious, intra-faith or interfaith dialogue. The action addresses Lot 1 by enhancing understanding and respect for cultural and religious diversity. It&#x2019;s strong focus on interreligious dialogue encourages the interaction between different religious denominations, particularly Islam and Christianity. However, traditional African beliefs and practices, which tend to be practised by practitioners of both Christianity and Islam, also play an important role in the target communities, sometimes causing conflict within the same denomination. The action will hence also have a positive impact on intra-faith dialogue. To reflect that the challenges communities are facing are neither solely cultural nor religious the language &#x2018;intercultural and interreligious pluralism&#x2019; has been followed throughout the proposal in line with the expected results defined by the European Commission.
Against the above background, the broader, long-term impact which the action will contribute to is to ensure that communities in Niger and Nigeria live in a culturally inclusive environment. This will be achieved through the direct outcome of the project which is that women and men and girls and boys in target communities contribute to and benefit from increased respect of cultural and religious pluralism. To enhance intercultural and interreligious tolerance, the action follows a fourfold approach by (iOc1) developing and disseminating academic and cultural material, (iOc2) strengthening networks and platforms, (iOc3) promoting public discourse and (iOc4) advocating for changes at government level. The community at large will benefit from the action in Nigeria.</narrative>
  </description>
